ince-edward-island-fever/|title=Prince Edward Island Fever|author=|date=8 February 2016|website=ontariomennonitehistory.org|accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref><ref>http://thecommonlife.com.au/c/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Let-Us-Reason-Together.wps_.pdf{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n{{Languages of Germany}}\n{{Languages of France}}\n{{Alsace topics}}\n{{Germanic languages}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alsatian Language}}\n[[Category:Alemannic German language]]\n[[Category:German dialects]]\n[[Category:Languages of France]]\n[[Category:Alsatian]]\n", "name_user": "Shanze1", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 313-336 \u2192 313\u2013336", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alsatian_dialect"}
{"title_page": "Nyla Ali Khan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox scholar\n| image            =  Nyla Ali Khan 3.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| birth_date       =  {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1972|4|28}}\n| birth_place      =  [[New Delhi]]\n| era              =  Modern\n| region           =  [[Jammu and Kashmir]], [[India]]\n| school_tradition = \n| main_interests   = \n| notable_ideas    = \n| major_works      = ''The Fiction of Nationality in an Era of Transnationalism'' and ''Islam, Women, and Violence in Kashmir: Between Indian and Pakistan'' \n| influences       = \n| influenced       = \n}}\n\n'''Dr. Nyla Ali Khan''' is a [[Visiting scholar|Visiting Professor]] at [[Rose State College]], former lecturer at the [[University of Oklahoma]], and former professor at the [[University of Nebraska-Kearney]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ou.edu/cas/english/people/faculty/facultypages/Khan.html|title=University of Oklahoma website|publisher=}}</ref> She is the author of four books, including ''The Fiction of Nationality in an Era of Transnationalism'' and ''Islam, Women, and Violence in Kashmir: Between Indian and Pakistan,'' and several articles that focus heavily on the political issues and strife of her homeland, [[Jammu and Kashmir]], India. Despite being the granddaughter of [[Sheikh Abdullah one who detonated kashmie]], Nyla Khan prefers not simply to live in his shadow but to \"stand up for myself and be taken seriously ... express my anger without being labeled an 'Islamic militant' ... [and] legitimately question things I don't understand\", as she stated in a 2010 interview related to the release of her second book.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epiloguemagazine.blogspot.com/2010/01/interview-with-nyla-ali-khan.html|title=Epilogue Magazine -Jammu and Kashmir: Interview with Nyla Ali Khan|last=Epilogue|date=26 January 2010|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://issuu.com/epilogue/docs/epilogue-november-2009 November 2009 Vol 3 Issue 12 p 38-41]</ref><ref>[http://issuu.com/epilogue/docs/epilogue December 2009 Vol 3 Issue 12 p 27-30]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nKhan was born in [[New Delhi]], India. Her family is based in [[Jammu and Kashmir]], [[India]] and she was raised there in the [[Kashmir Valley]] located in the foothills of the [[Himalayas]]. Her mother, Suraiya Abdullah Ali, is a retired professor of literature, and her father, Mohammad Ali Matto, is a retired physician. She is the only child of Suraiya Abdullah Ali and Mohammad Ali Matto\u2014and the granddaughter of [[Sheikh Abdullah]]. She did her Masters in Postcolonial Literature and Theory at the [[University of Oklahoma]], Norman, and obtained her Ph.D. at the same institution.\n\nIn May 2015, Khan was the first Kashmiri woman to be nominated and accepted as a member of the Advisory Council for the Oklahoma Commission on the Status of Women.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web | url=http://www.normantranscript.com/news/business/business-spotlight/article_cfb913cf-ec2a-5001-92de-2910a64557f8.html | title=Business spotlight}}</ref> The Council serves \"as a resource and clearinghouse for research and information on issues related to women and gender bias, to act as an advisory entity on equity issues to state agencies, communities, organizations and businesses of the state, and to establish recommendations for action to improve the quality of life for Oklahoma women, children and families.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books===\nIn her first book, ''The Fiction of Nationality in an Era of Transnationalism'', she \"examines the writings of [[V.S. Naipaul]], [[Salman Rushdie]], [[Amitav Ghosh]], and [[Anita Desai]], all four living abroad to explain the aberrant behaviour of emigres from the Indian subcontinent to explain why they support religious fundamentalist groups in India, Pakistan and Bangladesh.\"<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2006/20060902/saturday/above.htm | newspaper=The Tribune | location=India | title=Reap what you sow | date=2 September 2006 | first=Khushwant | last=Singh | accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref> In doing so, she strives to provide an objective view of how [[transnationalism]] can distort impressions of reality. In reviewing her book, [[Khushwant Singh]] notes that the transnational subjects examined by Dr. Khan \"having settled abroad, [...] develop an exaggerated sense of belonging, swallow fabricated history of their glorious pasts and despite having no intention of returning to the lands of their nativity give emotional and monetary support to subversive elements.\"<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*Review by Steven Salaita<ref>[http://www.upj.pitt.edu/7103/   ''South Asian Review,'' Vol. XXVII, No. 1 (2006): 274-275.]{{Dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn her second book, ''Islam, Women, and Violence in Kashmir: Between Indian and Pakistan,'' she examines [[women in Islam]] in \"the first th[o]rough study of the tragedy of Kashmir done by a Kashmiri woman.\"<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.unknews.com/UNK/story/?a=2812 | title=UNK - 'Islam, Women, and Violence in Kashmir: Between India and Pakistan' Focus of New Book by UNK's Dr. Nyla Ali Khan}}</ref> \"Khan uses the analytical tools of postmodern, feminist criticism to understand and highlight the role--passive and active--that women have played in Kashmir's history, ranging from the 14th century [[Lalleshwari|Lal Ded]], a mystic poet who laid the foundations of Kashmir's syncretic culture, to the present day Parveena Ahangar who represents the Association of the Parents of the Disappeared People.\"<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web | url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/site/Story/80428/Leisure/Blood+and+tears.html | title=Blood and tears}}</ref> Interspersed within are oral histories from women who serve to defend Kashmir from invasion, women who had previously been long ignored.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n*Review by Brian Hull in ''Genre'' Vol. 46, No. 1, Spring 2013, 103-108.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1215/00166928-1722953| title=Islam, Women, and Violence in Kashmir: Between India and Pakistan| journal=Genre| volume=46| pages=103\u2013105| year=2013| last1=Hull| first1=B.}}</ref>\n*Review by the University of Nebraska Kearney.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> \n*Review by Amitabh Mattoo in ''India Today,'' 22 January 2010<ref name=\"auto3\"/> \n*Review by Jaskiran Mathur in ''Journal of International Women\u2019s Studies'' Vol. 11 #1 November 2009, 328-332.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bridgew.edu/Soas/jiws/Nov09/index.htm | title=Journal of International Women's Studies &#124; Journals and Campus Publications &#124; Bridgewater State University}}</ref>\n*Review by Dr. Mustafa Kamal, \"Of women, politics and Kashmiriyat\" in ''Kashmir Times, Srinagar,'' Monday, 9 November 2009, 3-4. \n*Review by Seema Kazi in ''Conveyor,'' November 2009, 61-63\n\nShe undertakes the role of editor in a third book, ''The Parchment of Kashmir: History, Society, and Polity.'' The book presents a collection of essays by Kashmiri academics who are \"well-known, well-established, and well-respected within Kashmiri society\", but who haven\u2019t had much opportunity to reach an audience outside of Kashmir and outside of South Asia.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://gulftoday.ae/portal/5f067ae9-3eca-4a61-a04e-f8c148aadf8d.aspx | title=Latest news, comments and reviews from the Gulf Today &#124; gulftoday.ae}}</ref>\n\n*Review by Hari Jaisingh in ''Book Bazaar,'' 5 May 2013, 1-2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://harijaisingh.info/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/book-bazaar-The-Parchment-of-Kashmir_brhma.qxd_.pdf |title=Understanding facets of a complex syndrome |last=Jaisingh |first=Hari |date=2013 |website=harijaisingh.info |access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n*Review by David Taylor in ''Pakistaniaat: A Journal of Pakistan Studies,'' Vol. 5, No. 2 (2013), 137-8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pakistaniaat.org/index.php/pak/article/view/278/237 |title=Infi |website=pakistaniaat.org |format=PDF |access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n*Review by John C Hawley in ''Journal of Postcolonial Writing,'' 23 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tandfonline.com/eprint/edinjnNGsEYJyhfiUvrv/full#.UmpvExL3GAF | title=The parchment of Kashmir: History, society, and polity}}</ref>\n\nHer fourth book, ''The Life of a Kashmiri Woman: Dialectic of Resistance and Accommodation'' examines the life of her grandmother, Akbar Jehan \"paint[ing] a loving and personal picture of a powerful woman whose role and actions gave Kashmir a model for women's political action in the critical period before and after the partition of India in 1947.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.palgrave.com/page/detail/the-life-of-a-kashmiri-woman-nyla-ali-khan/?k=9781137465634&loc=uk | title=Palgrave}}</ref>\n\n*Review by Ellora Puri in ''The Book Review Literary Trust,'' 12 December 2014.<ref>[http://www.thebookreviewindia.org/articles/archives-4294/2014/December/12/tale-of-a-formidable-matriarch.html]{{Dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n*Review by Rehka Chowdhary in ''Oxford Islamic Studies Online,'' 19 April 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blog.oup.com/2015/04/kashmiri-politics-history-gender-perspective/ | title=A woman's journey in Kashmiri politics| date=2015-04-19}}</ref>\n\nShe has recently been working as an editor for a publication on the region of Jammu and Kashmir with Oxford Islamic Studies Online,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.oxfordislamicstudies.com/ | title=Oxford Islamic Studies Online - Oxford Islamic Studies Online}}</ref> which has been recruiting guest editors for projects that examine the \"politics, religious practices, economics, women\u2019s and minorities\u2019 rights, geography, arts and culture, [and] major figures\" of various Islamic regions. They will be including a featured article by her and plan to expand upon their partnership to provide additional materials to promote education and scholarship about the region.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globeistan.com/?p=48214 | title=Oxford Islamic Studies Online (announcement) \u00ab}}</ref>\n\nKhan\u2019s latest book, ''Sheikh Mohammad Abdullah\u2019s Reflections on Kashmir'', is a compendium of the speeches and interviews of [[Sheikh Abdullah|Sheikh Mohammad Abdullah]], who reigned as Prime Minister of the State of Jammu and Kashmir from 1948 to 1953, and who was a large presence on the political landscape of India for fifty years. The volume is designed to enable a student of South Asian politics, and the politics of Kashmir in particular, to analyze the ways in which experiences have been constructed historically and have changed overtime.\n<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://www.palgrave.com/us/book/9783319501024 | title=Sheikh Mohammad Abdullah's Reflections on Kashmir &#124; Nyla Ali Khan &#124; Palgrave Macmillan}}</ref>\n\n===Book chapters===\n*\"The Land of Lalla-Ded: Negation of \u2018Kashmiriyat\u2019 and Immiseration of the Kashmiri Woman.\" ''Contesting Nation: Gendered Violence in South Asia. Notes on the Postcolonial Present.'' Ed. Angana Chatterji and Lubna Nazir Chaudhry. New Delhi: Zubaan Books, 2010.\n*\"Citizenship in a Transnational Age: Culture and Politics in [[Amitav Ghosh]]\u2019s ''[[The Shadow Lines]].''\" In [[Amitav Ghosh]]\u2019s ''The Shadow Lines: A Critical Companion.'' Ed. Murari Prasad. Delhi: Pencraft International, 2007. Forthcoming.\n\n===Peer-reviewed articles===\n*\"Citizenship in a Transnational Age: Culture and Politics in Amitav Ghosh\u2019s ''The Shadow Lines.''\" ''The Journal of Indian Writing in English'' 33.2 (2005): 42-52.\n*\"Frederick Douglass : A Reinscriptive Discourse.\" ''World Literature Today 2''  (2001): 48-57.\n*\"The Reinscription of Dichotomies in [[Rushdie]]\u2019s Hybridized Protagonists.\"  ''Journal of South Asian Literature'' 35 (2000): 82-99.\n\n===Other articles===\n*\"The idealist who loved Kashmir: History revisited.\" ''Globeistan'' 3 April 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globeistan.com/?p=39952 | title=The idealist who loved Kashmir: History revisited \u00ab}}</ref>\n*\"Place and the Politics of Identity in Desai's In Custody.\" ''Atlantic Literary Review''  5.1-2 (2004): 128-145.\n*\"Faith that Moved Mountains.\" ''The Hindu'' OP-ED, 11 August 2012.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/article3751106.ece | title=Faith that moved mountains| newspaper=The Hindu| date=2012-08-10| last1=Khan| first1=Nyla Ali}}</ref>\n*\"Understanding Sheikh Muhammad Abdullah.\" ''Greater Kashmir: Srinagar'' Opinion, 7 November 2012.<ref>[http://www.greaterkashmir.com/news/2012/Nov/7/understanding-sheikh-muhammad-abdullah-27.asp]{{Dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n*\"Sheikh Mohammad Abdullah Some memories\" ''The News: International'' Political Economy, 9 December 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://jang.com.pk/thenews/dec2012-weekly/nos-09-12-2012/pol1.htm#7 | title=Daily Jang Urdu News &#124; Pakistan News &#124; Latest News - Breaking News}}</ref>\n*\"Muslim Women and Violent Protest: Kashmir.\" ''Encyclopedia of Women & Islamic Cultures.'' General Editor Suad Joseph. Brill Online, (Forthcoming, 2014)<ref>[http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopedia-of-women-and-islamic-cultures/muslim-women-and-violent-protest-kashmir-EWICCOM_002010]{{Dead link|date=June 2014}}</ref> \n*\"Home and Hearth\" ''Globeistan'' 25 September 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globeistan.com/?p=48808 | title=Home and Hearth \u00ab}}</ref>\n*\"Anita Desai\" (Nyla Ali Khan, 195-196); \"Amitav Ghosh\" (Nyla Ali Khan, 297-298) in the ''Encyclopedia of Literature and Politics: A-G''<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JcFC4oiDmpgC&q=nyla+khan#v=snippet&q=nyla%20khan&f=false | title=Encyclopedia of Literature and Politics: A-G| isbn=9780313329395| last1=Keith Booker| first1=M.| year=2005}}</ref>\n*\"Hope for peace: The cost of conflict in South Asia\" ''Edmondsun.com'' 19 December 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.edmondsun.com/opinion/hope-for-peace-the-cost-of-conflict-in-south-asia/article_b0619994-8801-11e4-9925-f70141ac790b.html | title=Hope for peace: The cost of conflict in South Asia}}</ref>\n*\"Kashmir solution can halt S. Asia\u2019s nuclear race\" ''Globeistan'' 28 January 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globeistan.com/?p=50893 | title=Kashmir solution can halt S. Asia's nuclear race \u00ab}}</ref>\n*\"Relevance of Sheikh\u2019s 1960 letter for today\u2019s Indo-Pak leaders\" ''Globeistan'' 8 September 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globeistan.com/?p=54470 | title=Relevance of Sheikh's 1960 letter for today's Indo-Pak leaders \u00ab}}</ref>\n*\"To have and to hold till death do us part: Mufti Mohammad Sayeed and the Indian National Congress\" ''Globeistan'' 8 January 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globeistan.com/?p=57122 | title=To have and to hold till death do us part: Mufti Mohammad Sayeed and the Indian National Congress \u00ab}}</ref>\n*\"Until Lions Have Their Historians, Tales of the Hunt Shall Always Glorify the Hunters: Sheikh Mohammad Abdullah, History Retold\" ''Counterpunch'' 22 January 2016<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2016/01/22/until-lions-have-their-historians-tales-of-the-hunt-shall-always-glorify-the-hunters-sheikh-mohammad-abdullah-history-retold/ | title=Until Lions Have Their Historians, Tales of the Hunt Shall Always Glorify the Hunters: Sheikh Mohammad Abdullah, History Retold}}</ref>\n*\"The Ambiguous Identity of a Kashmiri\" ''counterpunch'' 16 February 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2016/02/16/the-ambiguous-identity-of-a-kashmiri/ | title=The Ambiguous Identity of a Kashmiri}}</ref>\n*\"Several Captors Hold Kashmir Captive\" ''Globeistan'' 29 February 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globeistan.com/?p=58141 | title=Several Captors Hold Kashmir Captive \u00ab}}</ref>\n*\"Historical Distortions Galore\" ''counterpunch'' 11 April 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2016/04/11/historical-distortions-galore/ | title=Historical Distortions Galore}}</ref>\n\n===Media Contributions===\n*\"University of Oklahoma Visiting Professor Explores Life of Her Grandfather,\" Interview with Ashley Gibson, NewsOK, 14 May 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://newsok.com/university-of-oklahoma-visiting-professor-explores-life-of-her-grandfather/article/3809153 | title=University of Oklahoma visiting professor explores life of her grandfather| date=2013-05-14}}</ref>\n*\"We Must Try to Emerge as One Community,\" Interview with Afzal Sofi, Kashmir Reader, 8 August 2012.<ref>[http://www.kashmirreader.com/08102012-ND-%E2%80%98we-must-try-to-emerge-as-one-community%E2%80%99-2584.aspx]{{Dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n*\"Interview with Nyla Ali Khan,\", Epilogue, 26 January 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://epiloguemagazine.blogspot.com/2010/01/interview-with-nyla-ali-khan.html | title=Epilogue Magazine -Jammu and Kashmir: Interview with Nyla Ali Khan| date=2010-01-26}}</ref>\n*\"My Grandmother Died a Sad Woman,\" Interview with Riyaz Wani, Tehelka.com, Issue 9, Volume 12, 28 February 2015.<ref>[http://www.tehelka.com/my-grandmother-died-a-sad-woman/]{{Dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n*\"I seek to reinterpret the repressive framework of colonialism: Dr. Nyla Ali Khan,\" News Kashmir Magazine, 24 August 2015<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newskashmirmagazine.com/interview/i-seek-to-reinterpret-the-repressive-framework-of-colonialism-dr-nyla-ali-khan/ | title=I seek to reinterpret the repressive framework of colonialism: Dr. Nyla Ali Khan| date=2015-08-24}}{{Dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Conference presentations===\nShe co-organized the 2006 South Asian Literary Association Conference on \"Postcolonialism and South Asian Diasporas,\" which was held in conjunction with the [[Modern Language Association]] Conference in Philadelphia.  Over the years, she has had sixteen conference papers selected for presentation at major conferences, such as the South Asian Literary Association Conference, the Modern Language Association Conference, Annual British Commonwealth and Postcolonial Studies Conference, and the International Global Studies Conference.\n\nShe presented on \"Negotiating the Boundaries of Gender, Community, and Nationhood\" at the faculty Roundtable: \"Transnational Feminism and Research Methodology.\" Women\u2019s Studies Conference: \"No Limits 2008: Transnational Feminism.\" University of Nebraska at Kearney, Kearney, Nebraska, 1 Mar. 2008. She also chaired the panel on \"Traversing Political, National, and International Spaces.\" Women\u2019s Studies Conference: \"No Limits 2008: Transnational Feminism.\" She presented \"Rethinking State Formation in Kashmir,\" at the Institute for Public Knowledge, 5 October 2012. Furthermore, she had a presentation entitled \"Bridge Builders in the Kashmir Conflict: The Human Dimension and the Role of Civil Society,\" at the International Peace and Conflict Resolution Program, the Comparative and Regional Studies Program, the Center for Social Media, the Dialogue Development Group, and the Office of the University Chaplin at American University, 30 October 2012. She has given public lectures on her scholarly work at the California Institute of Integral Studies, San Francisco, and at the Center for Diaspora and Transnational Studies at the University of Toronto, Canada.\n\n*\"Kashmir: The Politics and History of a People,\" (with host Bryan Hull), Internationalization Initiative, 12 April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OAY3pyjari8|title=Nyla Khan at Portland Community College|last=PCC Videos|date=28 April 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n*\"Conversations with Dr. Nyla Ali Khan,\" (Sponsored by the West Wind Unitarian Church in Norman, OK), 7 February 2015.<ref>[https://fbcdn-sphotos-h-a.akamaihd.net/hphotos-ak-xfp1/v/t1.0-9/s720x720/10429343_10152939100336180_209351103431239707_n.jpg?oh=c871c96b852560681a624f074d7a4675&oe=54FD45D0&__gda__=1425640193_16f337fac07dbd7295a923e88400e5cd]{{Dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n*\"The Cost of Conflict in Southeast Asia,\" Rotary Club of Norman<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.normanrotary.org/Stories/dr-nyla-khan-%E2%80%9Cthe-cost-of-conflict-in-southeast-asia%E2%80%9D | title=Dr. Nyla Khan: \"The Cost of Conflict in Southeast Asia\"}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Nyla Ali}}\n[[Category:Writers from Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian women political writers]]\n[[Category:Indian political writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Indian women educational theorists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian educational theorists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian women scientists]]\n[[Category:Women writers from Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Scholars from Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Educators from Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Women educators from Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Abdullah political family]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox scholar\n| image            =  Nyla Ali Khan 3.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| birth_date       =  {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1972|4|28}}\n| birth_place      =  [[New Delhi]]\n| era              =  Modern\n| region           =  [[Jammu and Kashmir]], [[India]]\n| school_tradition = \n| main_interests   = \n| notable_ideas    = \n| major_works      = ''The Fiction of Nationality in an Era of Transnationalism'' and ''Islam, Women, and Violence in Kashmir: Between Indian and Pakistan'' \n| influences       = \n| influenced       = \n}}\n\n'''Dr. Nyla Ali Khan''' is a [[Visiting scholar|Visiting Professor]] at [[Rose State College]], former lecturer at the [[University of Oklahoma]], and former professor at the [[University of Nebraska-Kearney]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ou.edu/cas/english/people/faculty/facultypages/Khan.html|title=University of Oklahoma website|publisher=}}</ref> She is the author of four books, including ''The Fiction of Nationality in an Era of Transnationalism'' and ''Islam, Women, and Violence in Kashmir: Between Indian and Pakistan,'' and several articles that focus heavily on the political issues and strife of her homeland, [[Jammu and Kashmir]], India. Despite being the granddaughter of [[Sheikh Abdullah]], Nyla Khan prefers not simply to live in his shadow but to \"stand up for myself and be taken seriously ... express my anger without being labeled an 'Islamic militant' ... [and] legitimately question things I don't understand\", as she stated in a 2010 interview related to the release of her second book.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epiloguemagazine.blogspot.com/2010/01/interview-with-nyla-ali-khan.html|title=Epilogue Magazine -Jammu and Kashmir: Interview with Nyla Ali Khan|last=Epilogue|date=26 January 2010|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://issuu.com/epilogue/docs/epilogue-november-2009 November 2009 Vol 3 Issue 12 p 38-41]</ref><ref>[http://issuu.com/epilogue/docs/epilogue December 2009 Vol 3 Issue 12 p 27-30]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nKhan was born in [[New Delhi]], India. Her family is based in [[Jammu and Kashmir]], [[India]] and she was raised there in the [[Kashmir Valley]] located in the foothills of the [[Himalayas]]. Her mother, Suraiya Abdullah Ali, is a retired professor of literature, and her father, Mohammad Ali Matto, is a retired physician. She is the only child of Suraiya Abdullah Ali and Mohammad Ali Matto\u2014and the granddaughter of [[Sheikh Abdullah]]. She did her Masters in Postcolonial Literature and Theory at the [[University of Oklahoma]], Norman, and obtained her Ph.D. at the same institution.\n\nIn May 2015, Khan was the first Kashmiri woman to be nominated and accepted as a member of the Advisory Council for the Oklahoma Commission on the Status of Women.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web | url=http://www.normantranscript.com/news/business/business-spotlight/article_cfb913cf-ec2a-5001-92de-2910a64557f8.html | title=Business spotlight}}</ref> The Council serves \"as a resource and clearinghouse for research and information on issues related to women and gender bias, to act as an advisory entity on equity issues to state agencies, communities, organizations and businesses of the state, and to establish recommendations for action to improve the quality of life for Oklahoma women, children and families.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Books===\nIn her first book, ''The Fiction of Nationality in an Era of Transnationalism'', she \"examines the writings of [[V.S. Naipaul]], [[Salman Rushdie]], [[Amitav Ghosh]], and [[Anita Desai]], all four living abroad to explain the aberrant behaviour of emigres from the Indian subcontinent to explain why they support religious fundamentalist groups in India, Pakistan and Bangladesh.\"<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2006/20060902/saturday/above.htm | newspaper=The Tribune | location=India | title=Reap what you sow | date=2 September 2006 | first=Khushwant | last=Singh | accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref> In doing so, she strives to provide an objective view of how [[transnationalism]] can distort impressions of reality. In reviewing her book, [[Khushwant Singh]] notes that the transnational subjects examined by Dr. Khan \"having settled abroad, [...] develop an exaggerated sense of belonging, swallow fabricated history of their glorious pasts and despite having no intention of returning to the lands of their nativity give emotional and monetary support to subversive elements.\"<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*Review by Steven Salaita<ref>[http://www.upj.pitt.edu/7103/   ''South Asian Review,'' Vol. XXVII, No. 1 (2006): 274-275.]{{Dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn her second book, ''Islam, Women, and Violence in Kashmir: Between Indian and Pakistan,'' she examines [[women in Islam]] in \"the first th[o]rough study of the tragedy of Kashmir done by a Kashmiri woman.\"<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.unknews.com/UNK/story/?a=2812 | title=UNK - 'Islam, Women, and Violence in Kashmir: Between India and Pakistan' Focus of New Book by UNK's Dr. Nyla Ali Khan}}</ref> \"Khan uses the analytical tools of postmodern, feminist criticism to understand and highlight the role--passive and active--that women have played in Kashmir's history, ranging from the 14th century [[Lalleshwari|Lal Ded]], a mystic poet who laid the foundations of Kashmir's syncretic culture, to the present day Parveena Ahangar who represents the Association of the Parents of the Disappeared People.\"<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web | url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/site/Story/80428/Leisure/Blood+and+tears.html | title=Blood and tears}}</ref> Interspersed within are oral histories from women who serve to defend Kashmir from invasion, women who had previously been long ignored.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n*Review by Brian Hull in ''Genre'' Vol. 46, No. 1, Spring 2013, 103-108.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1215/00166928-1722953| title=Islam, Women, and Violence in Kashmir: Between India and Pakistan| journal=Genre| volume=46| pages=103\u2013105| year=2013| last1=Hull| first1=B.}}</ref>\n*Review by the University of Nebraska Kearney.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> \n*Review by Amitabh Mattoo in ''India Today,'' 22 January 2010<ref name=\"auto3\"/> \n*Review by Jaskiran Mathur in ''Journal of International Women\u2019s Studies'' Vol. 11 #1 November 2009, 328-332.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bridgew.edu/Soas/jiws/Nov09/index.htm | title=Journal of International Women's Studies &#124; Journals and Campus Publications &#124; Bridgewater State University}}</ref>\n*Review by Dr. Mustafa Kamal, \"Of women, politics and Kashmiriyat\" in ''Kashmir Times, Srinagar,'' Monday, 9 November 2009, 3-4. \n*Review by Seema Kazi in ''Conveyor,'' November 2009, 61-63\n\nShe undertakes the role of editor in a third book, ''The Parchment of Kashmir: History, Society, and Polity.'' The book presents a collection of essays by Kashmiri academics who are \"well-known, well-established, and well-respected within Kashmiri society\", but who haven\u2019t had much opportunity to reach an audience outside of Kashmir and outside of South Asia.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://gulftoday.ae/portal/5f067ae9-3eca-4a61-a04e-f8c148aadf8d.aspx | title=Latest news, comments and reviews from the Gulf Today &#124; gulftoday.ae}}</ref>\n\n*Review by Hari Jaisingh in ''Book Bazaar,'' 5 May 2013, 1-2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://harijaisingh.info/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/book-bazaar-The-Parchment-of-Kashmir_brhma.qxd_.pdf |title=Understanding facets of a complex syndrome |last=Jaisingh |first=Hari |date=2013 |website=harijaisingh.info |access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n*Review by David Taylor in ''Pakistaniaat: A Journal of Pakistan Studies,'' Vol. 5, No. 2 (2013), 137-8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pakistaniaat.org/index.php/pak/article/view/278/237 |title=Infi |website=pakistaniaat.org |format=PDF |access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n*Review by John C Hawley in ''Journal of Postcolonial Writing,'' 23 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tandfonline.com/eprint/edinjnNGsEYJyhfiUvrv/full#.UmpvExL3GAF | title=The parchment of Kashmir: History, society, and polity}}</ref>\n\nHer fourth book, ''The Life of a Kashmiri Woman: Dialectic of Resistance and Accommodation'' examines the life of her grandmother, Akbar Jehan \"paint[ing] a loving and personal picture of a powerful woman whose role and actions gave Kashmir a model for women's political action in the critical period before and after the partition of India in 1947.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.palgrave.com/page/detail/the-life-of-a-kashmiri-woman-nyla-ali-khan/?k=9781137465634&loc=uk | title=Palgrave}}</ref>\n\n*Review by Ellora Puri in ''The Book Review Literary Trust,'' 12 December 2014.<ref>[http://www.thebookreviewindia.org/articles/archives-4294/2014/December/12/tale-of-a-formidable-matriarch.html]{{Dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n*Review by Rehka Chowdhary in ''Oxford Islamic Studies Online,'' 19 April 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blog.oup.com/2015/04/kashmiri-politics-history-gender-perspective/ | title=A woman's journey in Kashmiri politics| date=2015-04-19}}</ref>\n\nShe has recently been working as an editor for a publication on the region of Jammu and Kashmir with Oxford Islamic Studies Online,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.oxfordislamicstudies.com/ | title=Oxford Islamic Studies Online - Oxford Islamic Studies Online}}</ref> which has been recruiting guest editors for projects that examine the \"politics, religious practices, economics, women\u2019s and minorities\u2019 rights, geography, arts and culture, [and] major figures\" of various Islamic regions. They will be including a featured article by her and plan to expand upon their partnership to provide additional materials to promote education and scholarship about the region.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globeistan.com/?p=48214 | title=Oxford Islamic Studies Online (announcement) \u00ab}}</ref>\n\nKhan\u2019s latest book, ''Sheikh Mohammad Abdullah\u2019s Reflections on Kashmir'', is a compendium of the speeches and interviews of [[Sheikh Abdullah|Sheikh Mohammad Abdullah]], who reigned as Prime Minister of the State of Jammu and Kashmir from 1948 to 1953, and who was a large presence on the political landscape of India for fifty years. The volume is designed to enable a student of South Asian politics, and the politics of Kashmir in particular, to analyze the ways in which experiences have been constructed historically and have changed overtime.\n<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://www.palgrave.com/us/book/9783319501024 | title=Sheikh Mohammad Abdullah's Reflections on Kashmir &#124; Nyla Ali Khan &#124; Palgrave Macmillan}}</ref>\n\n===Book chapters===\n*\"The Land of Lalla-Ded: Negation of \u2018Kashmiriyat\u2019 and Immiseration of the Kashmiri Woman.\" ''Contesting Nation: Gendered Violence in South Asia. Notes on the Postcolonial Present.'' Ed. Angana Chatterji and Lubna Nazir Chaudhry. New Delhi: Zubaan Books, 2010.\n*\"Citizenship in a Transnational Age: Culture and Politics in [[Amitav Ghosh]]\u2019s ''[[The Shadow Lines]].''\" In [[Amitav Ghosh]]\u2019s ''The Shadow Lines: A Critical Companion.'' Ed. Murari Prasad. Delhi: Pencraft International, 2007. Forthcoming.\n\n===Peer-reviewed articles===\n*\"Citizenship in a Transnational Age: Culture and Politics in Amitav Ghosh\u2019s ''The Shadow Lines.''\" ''The Journal of Indian Writing in English'' 33.2 (2005): 42-52.\n*\"Frederick Douglass : A Reinscriptive Discourse.\" ''World Literature Today 2''  (2001): 48-57.\n*\"The Reinscription of Dichotomies in [[Rushdie]]\u2019s Hybridized Protagonists.\"  ''Journal of South Asian Literature'' 35 (2000): 82-99.\n\n===Other articles===\n*\"The idealist who loved Kashmir: History revisited.\" ''Globeistan'' 3 April 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globeistan.com/?p=39952 | title=The idealist who loved Kashmir: History revisited \u00ab}}</ref>\n*\"Place and the Politics of Identity in Desai's In Custody.\" ''Atlantic Literary Review''  5.1-2 (2004): 128-145.\n*\"Faith that Moved Mountains.\" ''The Hindu'' OP-ED, 11 August 2012.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/article3751106.ece | title=Faith that moved mountains| newspaper=The Hindu| date=2012-08-10| last1=Khan| first1=Nyla Ali}}</ref>\n*\"Understanding Sheikh Muhammad Abdullah.\" ''Greater Kashmir: Srinagar'' Opinion, 7 November 2012.<ref>[http://www.greaterkashmir.com/news/2012/Nov/7/understanding-sheikh-muhammad-abdullah-27.asp]{{Dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n*\"Sheikh Mohammad Abdullah Some memories\" ''The News: International'' Political Economy, 9 December 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://jang.com.pk/thenews/dec2012-weekly/nos-09-12-2012/pol1.htm#7 | title=Daily Jang Urdu News &#124; Pakistan News &#124; Latest News - Breaking News}}</ref>\n*\"Muslim Women and Violent Protest: Kashmir.\" ''Encyclopedia of Women & Islamic Cultures.'' General Editor Suad Joseph. Brill Online, (Forthcoming, 2014)<ref>[http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopedia-of-women-and-islamic-cultures/muslim-women-and-violent-protest-kashmir-EWICCOM_002010]{{Dead link|date=June 2014}}</ref> \n*\"Home and Hearth\" ''Globeistan'' 25 September 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globeistan.com/?p=48808 | title=Home and Hearth \u00ab}}</ref>\n*\"Anita Desai\" (Nyla Ali Khan, 195-196); \"Amitav Ghosh\" (Nyla Ali Khan, 297-298) in the ''Encyclopedia of Literature and Politics: A-G''<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JcFC4oiDmpgC&q=nyla+khan#v=snippet&q=nyla%20khan&f=false | title=Encyclopedia of Literature and Politics: A-G| isbn=9780313329395| last1=Keith Booker| first1=M.| year=2005}}</ref>\n*\"Hope for peace: The cost of conflict in South Asia\" ''Edmondsun.com'' 19 December 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.edmondsun.com/opinion/hope-for-peace-the-cost-of-conflict-in-south-asia/article_b0619994-8801-11e4-9925-f70141ac790b.html | title=Hope for peace: The cost of conflict in South Asia}}</ref>\n*\"Kashmir solution can halt S. Asia\u2019s nuclear race\" ''Globeistan'' 28 January 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globeistan.com/?p=50893 | title=Kashmir solution can halt S. Asia's nuclear race \u00ab}}</ref>\n*\"Relevance of Sheikh\u2019s 1960 letter for today\u2019s Indo-Pak leaders\" ''Globeistan'' 8 September 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globeistan.com/?p=54470 | title=Relevance of Sheikh's 1960 letter for today's Indo-Pak leaders \u00ab}}</ref>\n*\"To have and to hold till death do us part: Mufti Mohammad Sayeed and the Indian National Congress\" ''Globeistan'' 8 January 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globeistan.com/?p=57122 | title=To have and to hold till death do us part: Mufti Mohammad Sayeed and the Indian National Congress \u00ab}}</ref>\n*\"Until Lions Have Their Historians, Tales of the Hunt Shall Always Glorify the Hunters: Sheikh Mohammad Abdullah, History Retold\" ''Counterpunch'' 22 January 2016<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2016/01/22/until-lions-have-their-historians-tales-of-the-hunt-shall-always-glorify-the-hunters-sheikh-mohammad-abdullah-history-retold/ | title=Until Lions Have Their Historians, Tales of the Hunt Shall Always Glorify the Hunters: Sheikh Mohammad Abdullah, History Retold}}</ref>\n*\"The Ambiguous Identity of a Kashmiri\" ''counterpunch'' 16 February 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2016/02/16/the-ambiguous-identity-of-a-kashmiri/ | title=The Ambiguous Identity of a Kashmiri}}</ref>\n*\"Several Captors Hold Kashmir Captive\" ''Globeistan'' 29 February 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://globeistan.com/?p=58141 | title=Several Captors Hold Kashmir Captive \u00ab}}</ref>\n*\"Historical Distortions Galore\" ''counterpunch'' 11 April 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2016/04/11/historical-distortions-galore/ | title=Historical Distortions Galore}}</ref>\n\n===Media Contributions===\n*\"University of Oklahoma Visiting Professor Explores Life of Her Grandfather,\" Interview with Ashley Gibson, NewsOK, 14 May 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://newsok.com/university-of-oklahoma-visiting-professor-explores-life-of-her-grandfather/article/3809153 | title=University of Oklahoma visiting professor explores life of her grandfather| date=2013-05-14}}</ref>\n*\"We Must Try to Emerge as One Community,\" Interview with Afzal Sofi, Kashmir Reader, 8 August 2012.<ref>[http://www.kashmirreader.com/08102012-ND-%E2%80%98we-must-try-to-emerge-as-one-community%E2%80%99-2584.aspx]{{Dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n*\"Interview with Nyla Ali Khan,\", Epilogue, 26 January 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://epiloguemagazine.blogspot.com/2010/01/interview-with-nyla-ali-khan.html | title=Epilogue Magazine -Jammu and Kashmir: Interview with Nyla Ali Khan| date=2010-01-26}}</ref>\n*\"My Grandmother Died a Sad Woman,\" Interview with Riyaz Wani, Tehelka.com, Issue 9, Volume 12, 28 February 2015.<ref>[http://www.tehelka.com/my-grandmother-died-a-sad-woman/]{{Dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n*\"I seek to reinterpret the repressive framework of colonialism: Dr. Nyla Ali Khan,\" News Kashmir Magazine, 24 August 2015<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newskashmirmagazine.com/interview/i-seek-to-reinterpret-the-repressive-framework-of-colonialism-dr-nyla-ali-khan/ | title=I seek to reinterpret the repressive framework of colonialism: Dr. Nyla Ali Khan| date=2015-08-24}}{{Dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Conference presentations===\nShe co-organized the 2006 South Asian Literary Association Conference on \"Postcolonialism and South Asian Diasporas,\" which was held in conjunction with the [[Modern Language Association]] Conference in Philadelphia.  Over the years, she has had sixteen conference papers selected for presentation at major conferences, such as the South Asian Literary Association Conference, the Modern Language Association Conference, Annual British Commonwealth and Postcolonial Studies Conference, and the International Global Studies Conference.\n\nShe presented on \"Negotiating the Boundaries of Gender, Community, and Nationhood\" at the faculty Roundtable: \"Transnational Feminism and Research Methodology.\" Women\u2019s Studies Conference: \"No Limits 2008: Transnational Feminism.\" University of Nebraska at Kearney, Kearney, Nebraska, 1 Mar. 2008. She also chaired the panel on \"Traversing Political, National, and International Spaces.\" Women\u2019s Studies Conference: \"No Limits 2008: Transnational Feminism.\" She presented \"Rethinking State Formation in Kashmir,\" at the Institute for Public Knowledge, 5 October 2012. Furthermore, she had a presentation entitled \"Bridge Builders in the Kashmir Conflict: The Human Dimension and the Role of Civil Society,\" at the International Peace and Conflict Resolution Program, the Comparative and Regional Studies Program, the Center for Social Media, the Dialogue Development Group, and the Office of the University Chaplin at American University, 30 October 2012. She has given public lectures on her scholarly work at the California Institute of Integral Studies, San Francisco, and at the Center for Diaspora and Transnational Studies at the University of Toronto, Canada.\n\n*\"Kashmir: The Politics and History of a People,\" (with host Bryan Hull), Internationalization Initiative, 12 April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OAY3pyjari8|title=Nyla Khan at Portland Community College|last=PCC Videos|date=28 April 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n*\"Conversations with Dr. Nyla Ali Khan,\" (Sponsored by the West Wind Unitarian Church in Norman, OK), 7 February 2015.<ref>[https://fbcdn-sphotos-h-a.akamaihd.net/hphotos-ak-xfp1/v/t1.0-9/s720x720/10429343_10152939100336180_209351103431239707_n.jpg?oh=c871c96b852560681a624f074d7a4675&oe=54FD45D0&__gda__=1425640193_16f337fac07dbd7295a923e88400e5cd]{{Dead link|date=June 2019}}</ref>\n*\"The Cost of Conflict in Southeast Asia,\" Rotary Club of Norman<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.normanrotary.org/Stories/dr-nyla-khan-%E2%80%9Cthe-cost-of-conflict-in-southeast-asia%E2%80%9D | title=Dr. Nyla Khan: \"The Cost of Conflict in Southeast Asia\"}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Nyla Ali}}\n[[Category:Writers from Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian women political writers]]\n[[Category:Indian political writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Indian women educational theorists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian educational theorists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian women scientists]]\n[[Category:Women writers from Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Scholars from Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Educators from Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Women educators from Jammu and Kashmir]]\n[[Category:Abdullah political family]]\n", "name_user": "2405:205:10b:9619::215d:70a4", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nyla_Ali_Khan"}
{"title_page": "Margaret Cuomo", "text_new": "{{short description|American radiologist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = Margaret I. Cuomo\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1955|3|29}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| occupation  = Physician, radiologist\n| spouse      = Peter Perpignano<br>(m. 1982; div. 19??)<br>{{marriage|Howard Simon Maier|1994}}\n| children    = 2\n| father = [[Mario Cuomo]]\n| mother = [[Matilda Cuomo|Matilda Raffa]]\n| relations   = {{ubl|[[Andrew Cuomo]] (brother)|[[Chris Cuomo]] (brother)}}\n| alma_mater  = {{ubl|[[St. John's University (New York City)|St. John's University]]|[[SUNY Downstate Medical Center]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Margaret I. Cuomo''' (born March 29, 1955) is an American radiologist, author, philanthropist, advocate, and blogger on health issues, especially those related to [[cancer]] prevention. She is the eldest child of former [[New York (state)|New York]] Governor [[Mario Cuomo]] and former New York [[First Lady]] [[Matilda Cuomo]], and sister to current New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] and journalist [[Chris Cuomo]]. She resides in New York.\n\n==Early life and education==\nCuomo was born in [[New York City]] to former [[New York (state)|New York]] Governor [[Mario Cuomo]] and former New York [[First Lady]] [[Matilda Cuomo]]. She grew up in Albany and Holliswood, Queens, New York, with her four siblings, [[Andrew Cuomo|Andrew]], Maria, Madeline, and [[Chris Cuomo|Chris]].\n\nShe attended High School in Jamaica Estates and graduated from The Mary Louis Academy, Class of 1973. She graduated from [[St. John's University (New York City)|St. John's University]] and received an M.D. degree from the [[SUNY Downstate Medical Center]] in [[Brooklyn, New York]] in 1981.\n\n==Professional career==\nCuomo is a board certified radiologist who practiced at [[North Shore University Hospital]] in [[Manhasset, New York|Manhasset]], New York.\nShe has specialized in body imaging, involving [[X-ray computed tomography|CT]], [[Ultrasound]], [[MRI]], and interventional procedures, much of her practice was dedicated to the diagnosis of cancer and [[AIDS]]. \nCuomo has been interviewed for and/or featured in magazines and newspapers, including Better Homes and Gardens, Education Update, Family Circle, Glamour, InStyle, Manhattan, Metro Newspapers, Networking, New York Daily News, O Magazine, Parade, People, Prevention, Redbook, Vogue and Women's Day, and on-line sites, including DoctorOz.com, Glamour.com, DailyBeast.com, and Prevention.com.<ref name=Purdue>{{cite web|last=Couzens|first=Bill|title=Margaret I. Cuomo, M.D. Speaks -- Purdue North Central Sinai Forum|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/bill-couzens/margaret-i-cuomo-md-speak_b_4391533.html|accessdate=2014-02-27}}</ref>\n\nCuomo gave the commencement speech at [[Dowling College]] on May 18, 2013, where she was also awarded an honorary Doctor of Science degree.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dowling College\u2019s 51st Commencement Ceremony|url=http://www.dowling.edu/commencement/2013/cuomo.php|accessdate=2014-02-25|date=2013-05-18|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140225211641/http://www.dowling.edu/commencement/2013/cuomo.php|archivedate=2014-02-25}}</ref>\n\n==Authorships==\nCuomo's book, ''A World Without Cancer: The Making of a New World and the Real Promise of Prevention'', was published October 2012 by [[Rodale, Inc.|Rodale]]. The book calls for improved coordination among government and academic research efforts and an elimination of unnecessary bureaucracy. The book also calls for making cancer prevention a U.S. priority by establishing a National Cancer Prevention Institute under the [[National Institutes of Health]] to coordinate research. Cuomo addresses weaknesses with cancer screening methods, doctor recommendation practices, and information patients are given regarding cancer. Cuomo argues for better efforts by pharmaceutical companies to prevent cancer through early detection, effective vaccines and new means of protecting the immune system. Cuomo also makes lifestyle recommendations for reducing cancer risk.<ref name=Cuomo>{{cite book|last=Cuomo|first=Margaret I.|title=A World Without Cancer: The Making of a New Cure and the Real Promise of Prevention|date=October 2012|publisher=Rodale|isbn=1609618858|url=https://archive.org/details/worldwithoutcanc0000cuom|url-access=registration}}</ref> Glamour Magazine interviewed her about the book October 10, 2012.<ref name=Glamour>{{cite web|last=Naugle|first=Wendy|title=When It Comes to the War on Cancer, Are We Settling for Treatments That Are \"Just Good Enough\"?|url=http://www.glamour.com/health-fitness/blogs/vitamin-g/2012/10/when-it-comes-to-the-war-on-ca.html|accessdate=2014-02-27}}</ref>\n\nCuomo contributes blog posts focusing on cancer prevention, the economic impact of cancer, and the need for reform.<ref name=Cuomo_HuffPo_Profile>{{cite web|last=Cuomo|first=Margaret I.|title=Margaret I. Cuomo, M.D.|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/margaret-i-cuomo-md/}}</ref> She also contributes to WebMD.<ref name=WebMD>{{cite web|last=Cuomo|first=Margaret|title=3 Ways to Reduce Cancer Risk|url=http://blogs.webmd.com/webmd-guests/2013/01/3-ways-to-reduce-cancer-risk.html|publisher=WebMD.com|accessdate=2014-02-27}}</ref> Cuomo has a [[Muckety]] score of 60.<ref>{{cite web|title=Margaret I. Cuomo|url=http://www.muckety.com/Margaret-Cuomo/18087.muckety|publisher=Muckety.com|accessdate=2014-02-25}}</ref>\n\n===Books===\n* Cuomo, M.I. (2012). ''A World Without Cancer: The Making of a New World and the Real Promise of Prevention.'' Rodale, Inc.\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn addition to her cancer prevention-related work, Cuomo has supported multiple initiatives to support Italian language education in the United States. She is the founder of [[The Italian Language Foundation]].\n\n==Honors==\nCuomo is an honoree of the Association of Italian American Educators (2003, 2005) and the National Organization of Italian American Women (2004). In 2011, Cuomo was awarded the \"Commendatore dell\u2019Ordine della Stella della Solidariet\u00e0 Italiana,\" the \"[[Order of the Star of Italian Solidarity]],\" by [[Giorgio Napolitano]], president of [[Italy]].<ref name=Star>{{cite news|last=Pirani|first=Alessia|title=Star of Italian Solidarity for Matilda Raffa Cuomo and Margaret Cuomo|url=http://www.i-italy.org/17460/star-italian-solidarity-matilda-raffa-cuomo-and-margaret-Cuomo|newspaper=i-Italy|date=2011-06-21}}</ref>\n\n==Memberships==\nCuomo is a member of the Medical Review Board of [[Huffington Post]].<ref name=Cuomo_HuffPo_Profile /> She is also a member of the [[Princeton University]] Advisory Council, French & Italian.<ref>{{cite web|title=French & Italian Advisory Council|url=http://www.princeton.edu/fit/people/advisory-council/|publisher=Princeton University|accessdate=2014-02-25|date=2011-10-13}}</ref> In 2007, she was listed as a member of the National Advisory Board of Concordia Language Villages. Cuomo was a member of the board of [[LessCancer.org]] 2013\u20132016.\n\n==Personal life==\nCuomo married Peter Perpignano October 10, 1982.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peter Perpignano, Builder, Marries Margaret Cuomo|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/10/11/style/peter-perpignano-builder-marries-margaret-cuomo.html|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=2014-02-25|date=October 11, 1982}}</ref> They later divorced. They have one daughter, Christina Cuomo Perpignano.<ref name=Hey_Grandpa>{{cite news|title=Hey Grandpa|url=http://209.212.22.88/Data/RBR/1980-1989/1985/1985.07.29.pdf|newspaper=The Register|date=1985-07-29|page=2A}}</ref> \n \nOn February 20, 1994, Cuomo married Howard Simon Maier.<ref>{{cite web|title=WEDDINGS; Margaret I. Cuomo, Howard S. Maier|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/02/20/style/weddings-margaret-i-cuomo-howard-s-maier.html|date= February 20, 1994|\npublisher=New York Times|accessdate=2014-02-25}}</ref> They have one daughter, Marianna Cuomo Maier.\n\n==See also==\n* [[The Italian Language Foundation]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{Andrew Cuomo |state=collapsed}}\n{{Mario Cuomo |state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cuomo, Margaret}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American radiologists]]\n[[Category:American women physicians]]\n[[Category:Women radiologists]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Campanian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:Cuomo family]]\n[[Category:St. John's University (New York City) alumni]]\n[[Category:SUNY Downstate Medical Center alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Queens, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Manhasset, New York]]\n[[Category:Andrew Cuomo]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American radiologist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = Margaret I. Cuomo\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1955|3|29}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| occupation  = Physician, radiologist\n| spouse      = Peter Perpignano<br>(m. 1982; div. 19??)<br>{{marriage|Howard Simon Maier|1994}}\n| children    = 2\n| father = [[Mario Cuomo]]\n| mother = [[Matilda Cuomo|Matilda Raffa]]\n| relations   = {{ubl|[[Andrew Cuomo]] (brother)|[[Chris Cuomo]] (brother)}}\n| alma_mater  = {{ubl|[[St. John's University (New York City)|St. John's University]]|[[SUNY Downstate Medical Center]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Margaret I. Cuomo''' (born March 29, 1955) is an American radiologist, author, philanthropist, advocate, and blogger on health issues, especially those related to [[cancer]] prevention. She is the eldest child of former [[New York (state)|New York]] Governor [[Mario Cuomo]] and former New York [[First Lady]] [[Matilda Cuomo]], and sister to current New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] and journalist [[Chris Cuomo]]. She resides in New York.\n\n==Early life and education==\nCuomo was born in [[New York City]] to former [[New York (state)|New York]] Governor [[Mario Cuomo]] and former New York [[First Lady]] [[Matilda Cuomo]]. She grew up in Albany and Holliswood, Queens, New York, with her four siblings, [[Andrew Cuomo|Andrew]], Maria, Madeline, and [[Chris Cuomo|Chris]].\n\nShe attended High School in Jamaica Estates and graduated from The Mary Louis Academy, Class of 1973. She graduated from [[St. John's University (New York City)|St. John's University]] and received an M.D. degree from the [[SUNY Downstate Medical Center]] in [[Brooklyn, New York]] in 1981.\n\n==Professional career==\nCuomo is a board certified radiologist who practiced at [[North Shore University Hospital]] in [[Manhasset, New York|Manhasset]], New York.\nShe has specialized in body imaging, involving [[X-ray computed tomography|CT]], [[Ultrasound]], [[MRI]], and interventional procedures, much of her practice was dedicated to the diagnosis of cancer and [[AIDS]]. \nCuomo has been interviewed for and/or featured in magazines and newspapers, including Better Homes and Gardens, Education Update, Family Circle, Glamour, InStyle, Manhattan, Metro Newspapers, Networking, New York Daily News, O Magazine, Parade, People, Prevention, Redbook, Vogue and Women's Day, and on-line sites, including DoctorOz.com, Glamour.com, DailyBeast.com, and Prevention.com.<ref name=Purdue>{{cite web|last=Couzens|first=Bill|title=Margaret I. Cuomo, M.D. Speaks -- Purdue North Central Sinai Forum|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/bill-couzens/margaret-i-cuomo-md-speak_b_4391533.html|accessdate=2014-02-27}}</ref>\n\nCuomo gave the commencement speech at [[Dowling College]] on May 18, 2013, where she was also awarded an honorary Doctor of Science degree.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dowling College\u2019s 51st Commencement Ceremony|url=http://www.dowling.edu/commencement/2013/cuomo.php|accessdate=2014-02-25|date=2013-05-18|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140225211641/http://www.dowling.edu/commencement/2013/cuomo.php|archivedate=2014-02-25}}</ref>\n\n==Authorships==\nCuomo's book, ''A World Without Cancer: The Making of a New World and the Real Promise of Prevention'', was published October 2012 by [[Rodale, Inc.|Rodale]]. The book calls for improved coordination among government and academic research efforts and an elimination of unnecessary bureaucracy. The book also calls for making cancer prevention a U.S. priority by establishing a National Cancer Prevention Institute under the [[National Institutes of Health]] to coordinate research. Cuomo addresses weaknesses with cancer screening methods, doctor recommendation practices, and information patients are given regarding cancer. Cuomo argues for better efforts by pharmaceutical companies to prevent cancer through early detection, effective vaccines and new means of protecting the immune system. Cuomo also makes lifestyle recommendations for reducing cancer risk.<ref name=Cuomo>{{cite book|last=Cuomo|first=Margaret I.|title=A World Without Cancer: The Making of a New Cure and the Real Promise of Prevention|date=October 2012|publisher=Rodale|isbn=1609618858|url=https://archive.org/details/worldwithoutcanc0000cuom|url-access=registration}}</ref> Glamour Magazine interviewed her about the book October 10, 2012.<ref name=Glamour>{{cite web|last=Naugle|first=Wendy|title=When It Comes to the War on Cancer, Are We Settling for Treatments That Are \"Just Good Enough\"?|url=http://www.glamour.com/health-fitness/blogs/vitamin-g/2012/10/when-it-comes-to-the-war-on-ca.html|accessdate=2014-02-27}}</ref>\n\nCuomo contributes blog posts focusing on cancer prevention, the economic impact of cancer, and the need for reform.<ref name=Cuomo_HuffPo_Profile>{{cite web|last=Cuomo|first=Margaret I.|title=Margaret I. Cuomo, M.D.|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/margaret-i-cuomo-md/}}</ref> She also contributes to WebMD.<ref name=WebMD>{{cite web|last=Cuomo|first=Margaret|title=3 Ways to Reduce Cancer Risk|url=http://blogs.webmd.com/webmd-guests/2013/01/3-ways-to-reduce-cancer-risk.html|publisher=WebMD.com|accessdate=2014-02-27}}</ref> Cuomo has a [[Muckety]] score of 60.<ref>{{cite web|title=Margaret I. Cuomo|url=http://www.muckety.com/Margaret-Cuomo/18087.muckety|publisher=Muckety.com|accessdate=2014-02-25}}</ref>\n\n===Books===\n* Cuomo, M.I. (2012). ''A World Without Cancer: The Making of a New World and the Real Promise of Prevention.'' Rodale, Inc.\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn addition to her cancer prevention-related work, Cuomo has supported multiple initiatives to support Italian language education in the United States. She is the founder of [[The Italian Language Foundation]].\n\n==Honors==\nCuomo is an honoree of the Association of Italian American Educators (2003, 2005) and the National Organization of Italian American Women (2004). In 2011, Cuomo was awarded the \"Commendatore dell\u2019Ordine della Stella della Solidariet\u00e0 Italiana,\" the \"[[Order of the Star of Italian Solidarity]],\" by [[Giorgio Napolitano]], president of [[Italy]].<ref name=Star>{{cite news|last=Pirani|first=Alessia|title=Star of Italian Solidarity for Matilda Raffa Cuomo and Margaret Cuomo|url=http://www.i-italy.org/17460/star-italian-solidarity-matilda-raffa-cuomo-and-margaret-Cuomo|newspaper=i-Italy|date=2011-06-21}}</ref>\n\n==Memberships==\nCuomo is a member of the Medical Review Board of [[Huffington Post]].<ref name=Cuomo_HuffPo_Profile /> She is also a member of the [[Princeton University]] Advisory Council, French & Italian.<ref>{{cite web|title=French & Italian Advisory Council|url=http://www.princeton.edu/fit/people/advisory-council/|publisher=Princeton University|accessdate=2014-02-25|date=2011-10-13}}</ref> In 2007, she was listed as a member of the National Advisory Board of Concordia Language Villages. Cuomo was a member of the board of [[LessCancer.org]] 2013-2016.\n\n==Personal life==\nCuomo married Peter Perpignano October 10, 1982.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peter Perpignano, Builder, Marries Margaret Cuomo|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/10/11/style/peter-perpignano-builder-marries-margaret-cuomo.html|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=2014-02-25|date=10/11/1982}}</ref> They later divorced. They have one daughter, Christina Cuomo Perpignano.<ref name=Hey_Grandpa>{{cite news|title=Hey Grandpa|url=http://209.212.22.88/Data/RBR/1980-1989/1985/1985.07.29.pdf|newspaper=The Register|date=1985-07-29|page=2A}}</ref> \n \nOn February 20, 1994, Cuomo married Howard Simon Maier.<ref>{{cite web|title=WEDDINGS; Margaret I. Cuomo, Howard S. Maier|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/02/20/style/weddings-margaret-i-cuomo-howard-s-maier.html|date= February 20, 1994|\npublisher=New York Times|accessdate=2014-02-25}}</ref> They have one daughter, Marianna Cuomo Maier.\n\n==See also==\n* [[The Italian Language Foundation]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{Andrew Cuomo |state=collapsed}}\n{{Mario Cuomo |state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cuomo, Margaret}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American radiologists]]\n[[Category:American women physicians]]\n[[Category:Women radiologists]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Campanian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:Cuomo family]]\n[[Category:St. John's University (New York City) alumni]]\n[[Category:SUNY Downstate Medical Center alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Queens, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Manhasset, New York]]\n[[Category:Andrew Cuomo]]\n", "name_user": "Jamesmcmahon0", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 2013-2016 \u2192 2013\u20132016", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margaret_Cuomo"}
{"title_page": "1971\u201372 Southern Football League", "text_new": "The '''1971\u201372 [[Southern Football League]] season''' was the 69th in the history of the league, an English [[Association football|football]] competition.\n\nAt the end of the previous season Division One was split into divisions One North and One South with 14 new clubs joining the league.\n\n[[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City]] won the championship, winning their third Southern League title, whilst [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion]], [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]], [[Ramsgate Athletic F.C.|Ramsgate Athletic]] and [[Waterlooville F.C.|Waterlooville]] were all promoted to the Premier Division. Eight Southern League clubs applied to join [[the Football League]] at the end of the season, [[Hereford United F.C.|Hereford United]] was elected in favour of [[Barrow A.F.C.|Barrow]] after a tie in the first vote.\n\n==Premier Division==\nThe Premier Division consisted of 22 clubs, including 18 clubs from the [[1970\u201371 Southern Football League#Premier Division|previous season]] and four new clubs, promoted from Division One:\n*[[Folkestone F.C.|Folkestone]]\n*[[Gravesend & Northfleet F.C.|Gravesend & Northfleet]]\n*[[Guildford City F.C.|Guildford City]]\n*[[Merthyr Tydfil F.C.|Merthyr Tydfil]]\n\n===League table===\n{{Infobox football league season\n|competition= Southern Football League<br>Premier Division\n|season=1971\u201372\n|winners= [[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City]]\n|relegated= [[Bath City F.C.|Bath City]]<br>[[Gloucester City F.C.|Gloucester City]]<br>[[Merthyr Tydfil F.C.|Merthyr Tydfil]]\n|matches= 462\n|total goals= 1378\n|prevseason= [[1970\u201371 Southern Football League#Premier Division|1970\u201371]]\n|nextseason= [[1972\u201373 Southern Football League#Premier Division|1972\u201373]]\n}}\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=PR\n|use_goal_ratio=y\n|winpoints=2\n|section=Premier Division\n\n|team1=CHC|name_CHC=[[Chelmsford City F.C.|Chelmsford City]]\n|team2=HER|name_HER=[[Hereford United F.C.|Hereford United]]\n|team3=DOV|name_DOV=[[Dover F.C.|Dover]]\n|team4=BRN|name_BRN=[[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]\n|team5=DAR|name_DAR=[[Dartford F.C.|Dartford]]\n|team6=WEY|name_WEY=[[Weymouth F.C.|Weymouth]]\n|team7=YEO|name_YEO=[[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]]\n|team8=HIL|name_HIL=[[Hillingdon Borough F.C.|Hillingdon Borough]]\n|team9=MAR|name_MAR=[[Margate F.C.|Margate]]\n|team10=WIM|name_WIM=[[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]]\n|team11=ROM|name_ROM=[[Romford F.C.|Romford]]\n|team12=GUI|name_GUI=[[Guildford City F.C.|Guildford City]]\n|team13=TEL|name_TEL=[[Telford United F.C.|Telford United]]\n|team14=NUN|name_NUN=[[Nuneaton Borough F.C.|Nuneaton Borough]]\n|team15=BED|name_BED=[[Bedford Town F.C.|Bedford Town]]\n|team16=WOR|name_WOR=[[Worcester City F.C.|Worcester City]]\n|team17=CMC|name_CMC=[[Cambridge City F.C.|Cambridge City]]\n|team18=FOL|name_FOL=[[Folkestone F.C.|Folkestone]]\n|team19=POO|name_POO=[[Poole Town F.C.|Poole Town]]\n|team20=BAT|name_BAT=[[Bath City F.C.|Bath City]]\n|team21=MER|name_MER=[[Merthyr Tydfil F.C.|Merthyr Tydfil]]\n|team22=GRA|name_GRA=[[Gravesend & Northfleet F.C.|Gravesend & Northfleet]]\n|win_CHC=28|draw_CHC=6|loss_CHC=8|gf_CHC=109|ga_CHC=46\n|win_HER=24|draw_HER=12|loss_HER=6|gf_HER=68|ga_HER=30\n|win_DOV=20|draw_DOV=11|loss_DOV=11|gf_DOV=67|ga_DOV=45\n|win_BRN=21|draw_BRN=7|loss_BRN=14|gf_BRN=80|ga_BRN=57\n|win_DAR=20|draw_DAR=8|loss_DAR=14|gf_DAR=75|ga_DAR=68\n|win_WEY=21|draw_WEY=5|loss_WEY=16|gf_WEY=69|ga_WEY=43\n|win_YEO=18|draw_YEO=11|loss_YEO=13|gf_YEO=67|ga_YEO=51\n|win_HIL=20|draw_HIL=6|loss_HIL=16|gf_HIL=64|ga_HIL=58\n|win_MAR=19|draw_MAR=8|loss_MAR=15|gf_MAR=74|ga_MAR=68\n|win_WIM=19|draw_WIM=7|loss_WIM=16|gf_WIM=75|ga_WIM=64\n|win_ROM=16|draw_ROM=13|loss_ROM=13|gf_ROM=54|ga_ROM=49\n|win_GUI=20|draw_GUI=5|loss_GUI=17|gf_GUI=71|ga_GUI=65\n|win_TEL=18|draw_TEL=7|loss_TEL=17|gf_TEL=83|ga_TEL=68\n|win_NUN=16|draw_NUN=10|loss_NUN=16|gf_NUN=46|ga_NUN=47\n|win_BED=16|draw_B