 A.F.C.|Bradford Park Avenue]]||[[Northern Premier League]]||align=right|1\n|-\n|[[Cambridge City F.C.|Cambridge City]]||[[Southern Football League|Southern League]]||align=right|1\n|-\n|[[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]]||[[Southern Football League|Southern League]]||align=right|1\n|-\n|[[Bangor City F.C.|Bangor City]]||[[Northern Premier League]]||align=right|0\n|-\n|[[Bedford Town F.C.|Bedford Town]]||[[Southern Football League|Southern League]]||align=right|0\n|-\n|[[Boston United F.C.|Boston United]]||[[Northern Premier League]]||align=right|0\n|-\n|[[Hillingdon Borough F.C.|Hillingdon Borough]]||[[Southern Football League|Southern League]]||align=right|0\n|-\n|[[Romford F.C.|Romford]]||[[Southern Football League|Southern League]]||align=right|0\n|-\n|[[Telford United F.C.|Telford United]]||[[Southern Football League|Southern League]]||align=right|0\n|-\n|[[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]||[[Northern Premier League]]||align=right|0\n|-\n|[[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]]||[[Southern Football League|Southern League]]||align=right|0\n|}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engsouthernleaghist.html RSSF \u2013 Southern Football League archive]\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Southern Football League seasons}}\n{{1971\u201372 in English football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1971-72 Southern Football League}}\n[[Category:Southern Football League seasons]]\n[[Category:1971\u201372 in English football leagues|S]]\n", "name_user": "Martinklavier", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDivision One North", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1971%E2%80%9372_Southern_Football_League"}
{"title_page": "Emil Urbel", "text_new": "{{short description|Estonian architect}}\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox architect\n| name                  = Emil Urbel\n| image                 = \n| image_size            = <!-- if image is smaller than 250px -->\n| alt                   = \n| caption               = \n| birth_name            = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date            = \n| birth_place           = \n| death_date            = \n| death_place           = \n| other_names           = \n| nationality           = \n| alma_mater            = \n| spouse                = \n| partner               = \n| children              = \n| parents               = \n| awards                = \n| practice              = <!--Associated architectural firm[s]-->\n| significant_buildings = \n| significant_projects  = \n| significant_design    = \n| signature             = \n| website               = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| embedded              = <!-- For embedding other infoboxes in this infobox -->\n}}\n\n'''Emil Urbel''' (born 13 November 1959 in [[P\u00e4rnu]]) is an [[Estonians|Estonian]] [[architect]].\n\nEmil Urbel studied in the State Art Institute of the Estonian SSR (today's [[Estonian Academy of Arts]]) in the department of [[architecture]]. He graduated from the institute in 1982.\n\nFrom 1984 to 1989 Emil Urbel worked in the state design bureau Eesti Projekt (Estonian National Design). From 1989 to 2000 he worked in the architectural bureau Urbel&Peil O\u00dc. From 2000 to present he works in the architectural bureau Emil Urbel O\u00dc.\n\nEmil Urbel is most notable for his numerous single-family homes. Most notable public buildings by Emil Urbel are the Rocca Al Mare School, the Kalev Spa and the Flour Mill building in the Rotermanni Quarter. For the Rocca Al Mare School building Emil Urbel received the annual award if the Estonian Cultural Endowment in 2000. Emil Urbel is a member of the [[Union of Estonian Architects]].\n\nHe, and some of his buildings, featured in the Jonathan Meades BBC programme \"Magnetic North\". (2008).\n\n==Works==\n*Terminal A of the Tallinn Passengers' Harbour, 1994 (with [[\u00dclo Peil]])\n*Hotell Central, 1994\n*Villa in Tabasalu, 1996\n*Estonian Law Institute 2000\n*Rocca al Mare School, 2000 (with \u00dclo Peil, Indrek Erm)\n*Aaviku housing area, 2003 (with Indrek Erm)\n*Restaurant Novell, 2004\n*Viinistu art museum, 2004\n*Villa in Miiduranna, 2004 (with Indrek Erm)\n*row housing on Esku Street, 2004\n*Kalev Spa, 2005\n*Frlour Mill in the Rotermanni Quarter, 2008 (with [[Ainar Luik]])\n*Nordea House, 2009 (with Indrek Erm)\n\n==References==\n#[http://www.arhliit.ee/en/the_union_of_estonia/members/alphabetical_registe?action=architect&architect_id=710 Union of Estonian Architects, members]\n#[https://web.archive.org/web/20091202061635/http://www.emilurbel.ee/cms/eesti/tootajad Architectural Bureau Emil Urbel O\u00dc, architects]\n#[https://web.archive.org/web/20090423012936/http://emilurbel.ee/cms/portfell Architectural Bureau Emil Urbel O\u00dc, works]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Estonian architects]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Urbel, Emil}}\n[[Category:Estonian architects]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from P\u00e4rnu]]\n\n\n{{Estonia-architect-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Estonian architect}}\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox architect\n| name                  = Emil Urbel\n| image                 = \n| image_size            = <!-- if image is smaller than 250px -->\n| alt                   = \n| caption               = \n| birth_name            = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date            = \n| birth_place           = \n| death_date            = \n| death_place           = \n| other_names           = \n| nationality           = \n| alma_mater            = \n| spouse                = \n| partner               = \n| children              = \n| parents               = \n| awards                = \n| practice              = <!--Associated architectural firm[s]-->\n| significant_buildings = \n| significant_projects  = \n| significant_design    = \n| signature             = \n| website               = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| embedded              = <!-- For embedding other infoboxes in this infobox -->\n}}\n\n'''Emil Urbel''' (born 13 November 1959 in [[P\u00e4rnu]]) is an [[Estonians|Estonian]] [[architect]].\n\nEmil Urbel studied in the State Art Institute of the Estonian SSR (today\u2019s [[Estonian Academy of Arts]]) in the department of [[architecture]]. He graduated from the institute in 1982.\n\nFrom 1984 to 1989 Emil Urbel worked in the state design bureau Eesti Projekt (Estonian National Design). From 1989 to 2000 he worked in the architectural bureau Urbel&Peil O\u00dc. From 2000 to present he works in the architectural bureau Emil Urbel O\u00dc.\n\nEmil Urbel is most notable for his numerous single-family homes. Most notable public buildings by Emil Urbel are the Rocca Al Mare School, the Kalev Spa and the Flour Mill building in the Rotermanni Quarter. For the Rocca Al Mare School building Emil Urbel received the annual award if the Estonian Cultural Endowment in 2000. Emil Urbel is a member of the [[Union of Estonian Architects]].\n\nHe, and some of his buildings, featured in the Jonathan Meades BBC programme \"Magnetic North\". (2008).\n\n==Works==\n*Terminal A of the Tallinn Passengers' Harbour, 1994 (with [[\u00dclo Peil]])\n*Hotell Central, 1994\n*Villa in Tabasalu, 1996\n*Estonian Law Institute 2000\n*Rocca al Mare School, 2000 (with \u00dclo Peil, Indrek Erm)\n*Aaviku housing area, 2003 (with Indrek Erm)\n*Restaurant Novell, 2004\n*Viinistu art museum, 2004\n*Villa in Miiduranna, 2004 (with Indrek Erm)\n*row housing on Esku Street, 2004\n*Kalev Spa, 2005\n*Frlour Mill in the Rotermanni Quarter, 2008 (with [[Ainar Luik]])\n*Nordea House, 2009 (with Indrek Erm)\n\n==References==\n#[http://www.arhliit.ee/en/the_union_of_estonia/members/alphabetical_registe?action=architect&architect_id=710 Union of Estonian Architects, members]\n#[https://web.archive.org/web/20091202061635/http://www.emilurbel.ee/cms/eesti/tootajad Architectural Bureau Emil Urbel O\u00dc, architects]\n#[https://web.archive.org/web/20090423012936/http://emilurbel.ee/cms/portfell Architectural Bureau Emil Urbel O\u00dc, works]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Estonian architects]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Urbel, Emil}}\n[[Category:Estonian architects]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from P\u00e4rnu]]\n\n{{Estonia-architect-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Shanze1", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emil_Urbel"}
{"title_page": "Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro|timestamp=20200405140103|year=2020|month=April|day=5|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro|date=5 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Advert|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Restaurant in Portland, Maine}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro is a pan-Asian, [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]] restaurant in [[Portland, Maine]] that opened in 2007 in the city's [[Arts District (Portland, Maine)|Arts District]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/trip-ideas/maines-best-restaurants-for-vegetarians|title=Maine\u2019s Best Restaurants for Vegetarians|last=Brian|first=Kevin|date=2015-06-08|website=Travel + Leisure|language=EN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> A second Green Elephant restaurant located in [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]] opened in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tasteoftheseacoast.com/component/content/article/16-restaurants/featured-restaurants/424-green-elephant-vegetarian-bistro-bar?Itemid=101|title=Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro & Bar|last=Miller|first=Kristyn Lak|date=2017-01-10|website=Taste of the Seacoast|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> It has received critical attention for its vegetarian dishes from non-vegetarians. \n\n== History ==\nThe restaurant was opened by chef Dan Sriprasert and business partner Bob Wongsaichua at 608 Congress Street across from the State Theatre building. Sriprasert and Wongsaichua also own Boda, a Thai restaurant located on Congress Street, and a second Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro in [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]]. The restaurant is named as green represents vegetarian cooking and elephants are considered lucky.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themainemag.com/blog/eat-maine-blog/2020-green-elephant-portland/|title=Green Elephant, Portland|last=Anderson|first=Amy K.|date=2012-09-20|website=The Maine Mag|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Menu ==\nThe menu is appetizers, stir fries, curries, noodle dishes and desserts. All the food is vegetarian and most is vegan. The chocolate orange mousse pie is often mentioned by food writers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vegnews.com/2012/8/15-east-coast-vegan-dishes-you-must-try|title=15 East Coast Vegan Dishes You Must Try|last=LAJEUNESSE|first=KRISTIN|date=2012-08-15|website=VegNews.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thesunriseguide.com/good-eats/|title=Good Eats {{!}} The best of Maine\u2019s healthy & vegetarian dining|last=Rusley|first=Erika Blauch|date=2013-08-30|website=The Sunrise Guide|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> \n\n== Reception ==\nThe restaurant doesn't take reservations and people sometimes wait outside for tables. In 2012, [[The Boston Globe]] travel writer Hilary Nangle said the restaurant \"has persuaded many carnivores that going veggie does not mean sacrificing flavor.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nangle|first=Hilary|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/travel/2012/04/28/maine-restaurants-where-vegetarian-fare-fills-plate-maine-restaurants-where-veggies-reign/Blys2jetRRnK6uzPhzQibI/story.html|title=10 Maine restaurants where vegetarians reign|date=2012-04-29|work=The Boston Globe|access-date=2020-04-01|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2013, Travel + Leisure named the restaurant to its list of the \"Best Vegetarian Restaurants in the U.S.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/food-drink/restaurants/best-vegetarian-restaurants-in-the-us|title=Best Vegetarian Restaurants in the U.S.|last=Sarah L.|first=Stewart|date=2013-08-10|website=Travel + Leisure|language=EN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> In 2016, the [[Portland Press Herald|Maine Sunday Telegram']]<nowiki/>s restaurant reviewer James H. Schwartz gave the restaurant three stars and wrote: \"It\u2019s fun, congenial and healthful, an easy place for vegetarians, dedicated carnivores \u2013 and the rest of us \u2013 to enjoy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2016/01/24/even-meat-lovers-will-find-plenty-to-like-at-green-elephant-an-asian-vegetarian-bistro-in-portland/|title=Dine Out Maine: Green Elephant in Portland|last=Schwartz|first=James H.|date=2016-01-24|website=Press Herald|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In 2019, The Daily Meal named the restaurant to its list of \"The Most Vegan-Friendly Restaurant in Every State.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailymeal.com/eat/best-vegan-restaurant-in-every-state|title=The most vegan-friendly restaurant in every state|last=Rock|first=Taylor|date=2019-11-19|website=The Daily Meal|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> In 2020, the [[Portland Press Herald]]'s vegan food writer Avery Yale Kamila called the restaurant Maine's \"reigning vegetarian restaurant queen.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2020/01/19/portlands-vegan-restaurant-scene-is-red-hot/|title=Vegan Kitchen: Portland\u2019s vegan restaurant scene is red-hot|last=Kamila|first=Avery Yale|date=2020-01-19|website=Press Herald|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Vegetarian restaurants]]\n[[Category:Maine]]\n[[Category:Portland, Maine]]\n[[Category:Thai restaurants]]\n[[Category:Vegan restaurants in the United States]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Maine]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Portland, Maine]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro|timestamp=20200405140103|year=2020|month=April|day=5|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro|date=5 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Advert|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Restaurant in Portland, Maine}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro is a pan-Asian, [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]] restaurant in [[Portland, Maine]] that opened in 2007 in the city's [[Arts District (Portland, Maine)|Arts District]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/trip-ideas/maines-best-restaurants-for-vegetarians|title=Maine\u2019s Best Restaurants for Vegetarians|last=Brian|first=Kevin|date=2015-06-08|website=Travel + Leisure|language=EN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> A second Green Elephant restaurant located in [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]] opened in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tasteoftheseacoast.com/component/content/article/16-restaurants/featured-restaurants/424-green-elephant-vegetarian-bistro-bar?Itemid=101|title=Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro & Bar|last=Miller|first=Kristyn Lak|date=2017-01-10|website=Taste of the Seacoast|language=en-gb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> It has received critical attention for its vegetarian dishes from non-vegetarians. \n\n== History ==\nThe restaurant was opened by chef Dan Sriprasert and business partner Bob Wongsaichua at 608 Congress Street across from the State Theatre building. Sriprasert and Wongsaichua also own Boda, a Thai restaurant located on Congress Street, and a second Green Elephant Vegetarian Bistro in [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]]. The restaurant is named as green represents vegetarian cooking and elephants are considered lucky.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themainemag.com/blog/eat-maine-blog/2020-green-elephant-portland/|title=Green Elephant, Portland|last=Anderson|first=Amy K.|date=2012-09-20|website=The Maine Mag|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Menu ==\nThe menu is appetizers, stir fries, curries, noodle dishes and desserts. All the food is vegetarian and most is vegan. The chocolate orange mousse pie is often mentioned by food writers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vegnews.com/2012/8/15-east-coast-vegan-dishes-you-must-try|title=15 East Coast Vegan Dishes You Must Try|last=LAJEUNESSE|first=KRISTIN|date=2012-08-15|website=VegNews.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thesunriseguide.com/good-eats/|title=Good Eats {{!}} The best of Maine\u2019s healthy & vegetarian dining|last=Rusley|first=Erika Blauch|date=2013-08-30|website=The Sunrise Guide|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> \n\n== Reception ==\nThe restaurant doesn't take reservations and people sometimes wait outside for tables. In 2012, [[The Boston Globe]] travel writer Hilary Nangle said the restaurant \"has persuaded many carnivores that going veggie does not mean sacrificing flavor.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nangle|first=Hilary|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/travel/2012/04/28/maine-restaurants-where-vegetarian-fare-fills-plate-maine-restaurants-where-veggies-reign/Blys2jetRRnK6uzPhzQibI/story.html|title=10 Maine restaurants where vegetarians reign|date=2012-04-29|work=The Boston Globe|access-date=2020-04-01|url-status=live}}</ref> in 2013, Travel + Leisure named the restaurant to its list of the \"Best Vegetarian Restaurants in the U.S.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/food-drink/restaurants/best-vegetarian-restaurants-in-the-us|title=Best Vegetarian Restaurants in the U.S.|last=Sarah L.|first=Stewart|date=2013-08-10|website=Travel + Leisure|language=EN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> In 2016, the [[Portland Press Herald|Maine Sunday Telegram']]<nowiki/>s restaurant reviewer James H. Schwartz gave the restaurant three stars and wrote: \"It\u2019s fun, congenial and healthful, an easy place for vegetarians, dedicated carnivores \u2013 and the rest of us \u2013 to enjoy.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2016/01/24/even-meat-lovers-will-find-plenty-to-like-at-green-elephant-an-asian-vegetarian-bistro-in-portland/|title=Dine Out Maine: Green Elephant in Portland|last=Schwartz|first=James H.|date=2016-01-24|website=Press Herald|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In 2019, The Daily Meal named the restaurant to its list of \"The Most Vegan-Friendly Restaurant in Every State.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailymeal.com/eat/best-vegan-restaurant-in-every-state|title=The most vegan-friendly restaurant in every state|last=Rock|first=Taylor|date=2019-11-19|website=The Daily Meal|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> In 2020, the [[Portland Press Herald]]'s vegan food writer Avery Yale Kamila called the restaurant Maine's \"reigning vegetarian restaurant queen.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2020/01/19/portlands-vegan-restaurant-scene-is-red-hot/|title=Vegan Kitchen: Portland\u2019s vegan restaurant scene is red-hot|last=Kamila|first=Avery Yale|date=2020-01-19|website=Press Herald|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Vegetarian restaurants]]\n[[Category:Maine]]\n[[Category:Portland, Maine]]\n[[Category:Thai restaurants]]\n[[Category:Vegan restaurants in the United States]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Maine]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Portland, Maine]]\n", "name_user": "BrikDuk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception:fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Elephant_Vegetarian_Bistro"}
